study_protocol_1: Anemia in IF Protocol _ v 2.0 2022-01-20 UofC  copy.docx
ma_hypotheses:
Primary Aim: to determine the prevalence of iron deficiency anemia, anemia of inflammation, mixed iron deficiency anemia/anemia of inflammation  and nutritional anemia in children with intestinal failure.
Secondary aim: to identify factors associated with the varied types of anemia in children with intestinal failure.
ma_data_desc: The data includes continuous variables (e.g. laboratory values  - each with their own specific units of measure, patient height/weight), as well as categorical variables relating to patient demographics/anatomy/surgical history as well as status/history of liver disease, renal disease, GI bleeds, etc (see Table 6 in the protocol). Combinations of various lab values are used to classify the presence and type of anemia at a given time point. The study is cross-sectional with a 10-year retrospective chart review, so there are up to 10 time points for a patient with all of the variables and hence, there are repeated measures.
ma_data_variables_main:
Outcome: Anemia (iron deficiency, anemia of inflammation, mixed, nutritional)
Predictors/Exposure: SBS status, history of step, presence of ICV, liver disease, renal disease, PN duration, GI bleed, SIBO, histological inflammation, micronutrient deficiencies
ma_stat_methods: We have a plan for all of the descriptive statistics, but need some guidance with how to approach the regression analysis.
other_questions: We need some guidance with the best approach to the regression analysis given there are multiple outcomes (different types of anemia) , and because we are also dealing with repeated measures. The number of repeat measures varies for each patient (ranges from 1-10 time points) and a single patient may have a different type of anemia at different time points.

project_title: Investigating Midlife Physical Activity and Cognition Trial: Pilot (IMPACT Pilot)
ma_hypotheses: The objective of this assessor-blind, proof-of-concept RCT is to determine the efficacy of a 6-month, 3x/week AT intervention on cognition during midlife, a critical window for the emergence of compromised brain health in females, and to determine the moderating effects of biological sex and APOE4. This project has 3 specific aims: Primary Aim. Determine whether AT is effective in promoting cognition in midlife. Secondary Aim. Determine whether biological sex and APOE4 genotype are moderators of AT efficacy. Tertiary Aim. Assess the effects of AT on potential mediators: 1) serum BDNF; 2) the HPA axis functioning; 3) serum hormones E2, E1, T, androstenedione; and 4) cardiometabolic risk profile. I hypothesize that midlife APOE4 females will show the greatest positive cognitive gains from AT levels compared with males. AT-induced cognitive gains in females will correlate with serum mature BDNF levels, salivary cortisol levels, serum levels of E2, E1 and androstenedione, and cardiometabolic indices.
ma_data_desc:

specific_requirement_other:
I have a single instrument database running as a service on a UCIT secure level 4 server. For various reasons, I wish to convert this to REDCap. It collects data on a fully operational clinical care pathway for head and neck cancer patients. Our pathway has been operational for over a decade and we have been prospectively collecting data (manually) the entire time.

Our intent at present is to continue with manual data abstraction and collection as we currently do, albeit in REDCap rather than our current setup. I have no experience creating REDCap instruments. I know I could build it given enough time and trial and error. I would also like to know what the cost and timeline would be for you to do it for us.

There is also the longer term potential to have automated data capture take place from ConnectCare. I don't know what hoops we need to jump through to accomplish this, but I would appreciate the discussion.

ma_hypotheses:
1.	Define the prevalence of familial pulmonary fibrosis (FPF) and non-FPF in CARE-PF. Diagnosis will be based on CAREPF diagnosis and defined as PF and a patient reported history of an affected family member.
2.	Describe the clinical diagnoses associated stratified by FPF and non-FPF in CAREPF.
3.	Describe the radiologic characteristics associated with FPF (MDD study data only), and compare differences with non-FPF diagnoses
4.	Compare clinical outcomes in FPF patients compared to non-FPF patients, overall and within key diagnostic subgroups.
ma_data_desc: Demographics, CARE-PF diagnosis, treatment, longitudinal pulmonary function testing, date of death or transplant, radiologic pattern and quantification.
ma_data_filter: all patients in data set 1, will require linkage to data set 2 for outcome data
ma_data_variables_main: Data will be presented as mean  standard deviation (SD) or median and interquartile range (IQR) for continuous variables and percentages for categorical variables. Pearson chi-square will be used to analyze categorical variables of FPF and non-FPF diagnosis and radiologic patterns. Transplant free survival or death will be compared using a mixed effects Cox regression model, adjusted for age, sex, smoking, baseline lung function, treatment, overall and stratified by diagnostic sub-groups.

other_questions:
This is more a public health initiative to see if the current process of migraine being referred and managed by the primary care physicians is actually improving the access and care of our migraine patients while reducing the health care cost. 
We would like to request for the cost-estimate as well to assist with these analysis, especially the health  care cost.
